[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/finite-volume-method] The **finite volume method** (**FVM**) is a method for representing and evaluating partial differential equations in the form of algebraic equations.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/finite-volume-method] In the finite volume method, volume integrals in a partial differential equation that contain a divergence term are converted to surface integrals, using the divergence theorem.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/finite-volume-method] These terms are then evaluated as fluxes at the surfaces of each finite volume.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/finite-volume-method] Because the flux entering a given volume is identical to that leaving the adjacent volume, these methods are conservative.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/finite-volume-method] Another advantage of the finite volume method is that it is easily formulated to allow for unstructured meshes.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/finite-volume-method] The method is used in many computational fluid dynamics packages.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/finite-volume-method] "Finite volume" refers to the small volume surrounding each node point on a mesh.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/finite-volume-method] Finite volume methods can be compared and contrasted with the finite difference methods, which approximate derivatives using nodal values, or finite element methods, which create local approximations of a solution using local data, and construct a global approximation by stitching them together.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/finite-volume-method] In contrast a finite volume method evaluates exact expressions for the *average* value of the solution over some volume, and uses this data to construct approximations of the solution within cells.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/finite-volume-method] Here, $\rho =\rho \left(x,t\right)$ represents the state variable and $f=f\left(\rho \left(x,t\right)\right)$ represents the flux or flow of $\rho$ .
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/finite-volume-method] Conventionally, positive f represents flow to the right while negative f represents flow to the left.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/finite-volume-method] If we assume that equation (**1**) represents a flowing medium of constant area, we can sub-divide the spatial domain, x , into *finite volumes* or *cells* with cell centers indexed as i .
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/finite-volume-method] where $x_{i-1/2}$ and $x_{i+1/2}$ represent locations of the upstream and downstream faces or edges respectively of the $i^{\text{th}}$ cell.
