[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] The simulation of turbulent flows by numerically solving the Navier–Stokes equations requires resolving a very wide range of time and length scales, all of which affect the flow field.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] Such a resolution can be achieved with direct numerical simulation (DNS), but DNS is computationally expensive, and its cost prohibits simulation of practical engineering systems with complex geometry or flow configurations, such as turbulent jets, pumps, vehicles, and landing gear.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] The principal idea behind LES is to reduce the computational cost by ignoring the smallest length scales, which are the most computationally expensive to resolve, via low-pass filtering of the Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] Such a low-pass filtering, which can be viewed as a time- and spatial-averaging, effectively removes small-scale information from the numerical solution.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] This information is not irrelevant, however, and its effect on the flow field must be modelled, a task which is an active area of research for problems in which small-scales can play an important role, such as near-wall flows, reacting flows, and multiphase flows.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] An LES filter can be applied to a spatial and temporal field $\phi ({\boldsymbol {x}},t)$ and perform a spatial filtering operation, a temporal filtering operation, or both.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] where G is the filter convolution kernel.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] The filter kernel G has an associated cutoff length scale $\Delta$ and cutoff time scale $\tau _{c}$ .
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] Scales smaller than these are eliminated from ${\overline {\phi }}$ .
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] It is important to note that the large eddy simulation filtering operation does not satisfy the properties of a Reynolds operator.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] The governing equations of LES are obtained by filtering the partial differential equations governing the flow field $\rho {\boldsymbol {u}}({\boldsymbol {x}},t)$ .
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] There are differences between the incompressible and compressible LES governing equations, which lead to the definition of a new filtering operation.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] where ${\bar {p}}$ is the filtered pressure field and ${\bar {S}}_{ij}$ is the rate-of-strain tensor evaluated using the filtered velocity.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] The nonlinear filtered advection term ${\overline {u_{i}u_{j}}}$ is the chief cause of difficulty in LES modeling.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] It requires knowledge of the unfiltered velocity field, which is unknown, so it must be modeled.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] The analysis that follows illustrates the difficulty caused by the nonlinearity, namely, that it causes interaction between large and small scales, preventing separation of scales.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] with the residual stress tensor $\tau _{ij}$ grouping all unclosed terms.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] Modeling the unclosed term $\tau _{ij}$ is the task of sub-grid scale (SGS) models.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] This is made challenging by the fact that the subgrid stress tensor $\tau _{ij}$ must account for interactions among all scales, including filtered scales with unfiltered scales.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] where $J_{\phi }$ is the diffusive flux of $\phi$ , and $q_{j}$ is the sub-filter flux for the scalar $\phi$ .
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] and can similarly be split up into contributions from interactions between various scales.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] This sub-filter flux also requires a sub-filter model.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] This equation models the changes in time of the filtered variables ${\bar {u}}_{i}$ .
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] Since the unfiltered variables $u_{i}$ are not known, it is impossible to directly calculate ${\overline {\frac {\partial u_{i}u_{j}}{\partial x_{j}}}}$ .
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] For the governing equations of compressible flow, each equation, starting with the conservation of mass, is filtered.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] which results in an additional sub-filter term.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] However, it is desirable to avoid having to model the sub-filter scales of the mass conservation equation.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] which, in the limit of incompressibility, becomes the normal filtering operation.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] This concept can then be extended to write the Favre-filtered momentum equation for compressible flow.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] and the term ${\frac {\partial }{\partial x_{j}}}\left({\overline {\sigma }}_{ij}-{\tilde {\sigma }}_{ij}\right)$ represents a sub-filter viscous contribution from evaluating the viscosity $\mu (T)$ using the Favre-filtered temperature ${\tilde {T}}$ .
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] By analogy, the Leonard decomposition may also be written for the residual stress tensor for a filtered triple product ${\overline {\rho \phi \psi }}$ .
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] The triple product can be rewritten using the Favre filtering operator as ${\overline {\rho }}{\widetilde {\phi \psi }}$ , which is an unclosed term (it requires knowledge of the fields $\phi$ and $\psi$ , when only the fields ${\tilde {\phi }}$ and ${\tilde {\psi }}$ are known).
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] It can be broken up in a manner analogous to ${\overline {u_{i}u_{j}}}$ above, which results in a sub-filter stress tensor ${\overline {\rho }}\left({\widetilde {\phi \psi }}-{\tilde {\phi }}{\tilde {\psi }}\right)$ .
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] In addition to the filtered mass and momentum equations, filtering the kinetic energy equation can provide additional insight.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] where $\epsilon _{f}=2\nu {\bar {S}}_{ij}{\bar {S}}_{ij}$ is the dissipation of kinetic energy of the filtered velocity field by viscous stress, and $\Pi =-\tau _{ij}^{r}{\bar {S}}_{ij}$ represents the sub-filter scale (SFS) dissipation of kinetic energy.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] The terms on the left-hand side represent transport, and the terms on the right-hand side are sink terms that dissipate kinetic energy.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] The $\Pi$ SFS dissipation term is of particular interest, since it represents the transfer of energy from large resolved scales to small unresolved scales.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] On average, $\Pi$ transfers energy from large to small scales.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] However, instantaneously $\Pi$ can be positive *or* negative, meaning it can also act as a source term for $E_{f}$ , the kinetic energy of the filtered velocity field.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] The transfer of energy from unresolved to resolved scales is called **backscatter** (and likewise the transfer of energy from resolved to unresolved scales is called **forward-scatter**).
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] Large eddy simulation involves the solution to the discrete filtered governing equations using computational fluid dynamics.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] LES resolves scales from the domain size L down to the filter size $\Delta$ , and as such a substantial portion of high wave number turbulent fluctuations must be resolved.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] This requires either high-order numerical schemes, or fine grid resolution if low-order numerical schemes are used.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] Chapter 13 of Pope addresses the question of how fine a grid resolution $\Delta x$ is needed to resolve a filtered velocity field ${\overline {u}}({\boldsymbol {x}})$ .
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] Ghosal found that for low-order discretization schemes, such as those used in finite volume methods, the truncation error can be the same order as the subfilter scale contributions, unless the filter width $\Delta$ is considerably larger than the grid spacing $\Delta x$ .
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] While even-order schemes have truncation error, they are non-dissipative, and because subfilter scale models are dissipative, even-order schemes will not affect the subfilter scale model contributions as strongly as dissipative schemes.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] The filtering operation in large eddy simulation can be implicit or explicit.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] Implicit filtering recognizes that the subfilter scale model will dissipate in the same manner as many numerical schemes.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] In this way, the grid, or the numerical discretization scheme, can be assumed to be the LES low-pass filter.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] While this takes full advantage of the grid resolution, and eliminates the computational cost of calculating a subfilter scale model term, it is difficult to determine the shape of the LES filter that is associated with some numerical issues.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] Additionally, truncation error can also become an issue.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] In explicit filtering, an LES filter is applied to the discretized Navier–Stokes equations, providing a well-defined filter shape and reducing the truncation error.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] However, explicit filtering requires a finer grid than implicit filtering, and the computational cost increases with $(\Delta x)^{4}$ .
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] Chapter 8 of Sagaut (2006) covers LES numerics in greater detail.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] Inlet boundary conditions affect the accuracy of LES significantly, and the treatment of inlet conditions for LES is a complicated problem.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] (3) being easy to implement and adjust to different cases.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] The first method for generating turbulent inlets is to synthesize them according to particular cases, such as Fourier techniques, principle orthogonal decomposition (POD) and vortex methods.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] The synthesis techniques attempt to construct turbulent field at inlets that have suitable turbulence-like properties and make it easy to specify parameters of the turbulence, such as turbulent kinetic energy and turbulent dissipation rate.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] In addition, inlet conditions generated by using random numbers are computationally inexpensive.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] However, one serious drawback exists in the method.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] The synthesized turbulence does not satisfy the physical structure of fluid flow governed by Navier-Stokes equations.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] The second method involves a separate and precursor calculation to generate a turbulent database which can be introduced into the main computation at the inlets.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] The database (sometimes named as ‘library’) can be generated in a number of ways, such as cyclic domains, pre-prepared library, and internal mapping.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] However, the method of generating turbulent inflow by precursor simulations requires large calculation capacity.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] Researchers examining the application of various types of synthetic and precursor calculations have found that the more realistic the inlet turbulence, the more accurate LES predicts results.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] To discuss the modeling of unresolved scales, first the unresolved scales must be classified.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] They fall into two groups: **resolved sub-filter scales** (SFS), and **sub-grid scales**(SGS).
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] The resolved sub-filter scales represent the scales with wave numbers larger than the cutoff wave number $k_{c}$ , but whose effects are dampened by the filter.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] Resolved sub-filter scales only exist when filters non-local in wave-space are used (such as a box or Gaussian filter).
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] These resolved sub-filter scales must be modeled using filter reconstruction.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] Sub-grid scales are any scales that are smaller than the cutoff filter width $\Delta$ .
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] The form of the SGS model depends on the filter implementation.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] As mentioned in the Numerical methods for LES section, if implicit LES is considered, no SGS model is implemented and the numerical effects of the discretization are assumed to mimic the physics of the unresolved turbulent motions.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] Without a universally valid description of turbulence, empirical information must be utilized when constructing and applying SGS models, supplemented with fundamental physical constraints such as Galilean invariance .
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] Two classes of SGS models exist; the first class is **functional models** and the second class is **structural models**.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] Functional models are simpler than structural models, focusing only on dissipating energy at a rate that is physically correct.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] These are based on an artificial eddy viscosity approach, where the effects of turbulence are lumped into a turbulent viscosity.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] The approach treats dissipation of kinetic energy at sub-grid scales as analogous to molecular diffusion.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] Based on dimensional analysis, the eddy viscosity must have units of $\left[\nu _{\mathrm {t} }\right]={\frac {\mathrm {m^{2}} }{\mathrm {s} }}$ .
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] Most eddy viscosity SGS models model the eddy viscosity as the product of a characteristic length scale and a characteristic velocity scale.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] The first SGS model developed was the Smagorinsky–Lilly SGS model, which was developed by Smagorinsky and used in the first LES simulation by Deardorff.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] where $\Delta$ is the grid size and C is a constant.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] This method assumes that the energy production and dissipation of the small scales are in equilibrium - that is, $\epsilon =\Pi$ .
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] Germano et al. identified a number of studies using the Smagorinsky model that each found different values for the Smagorinsky constant C for different flow configurations.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] In an attempt to formulate a more universal approach to SGS models, Germano et al. proposed a dynamic Smagorinsky model, which utilized two filters: a grid LES filter, denoted ${\overline {f}}$ , and a test LES filter, denoted ${\hat {f}}$ for any turbulent field f .
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] The test filter is larger in size than the grid filter and adds an additional smoothing of the turbulence field over the already smoothed fields represented by the LES.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] Germano *et* al. noted that even though neither $\tau _{ij}$ nor $T_{ij}$ can be computed exactly because of the presence of unresolved scales, there is an exact relation connecting these two tensors.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] In order to do this, two additional steps were introduced in the original formulation.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] First, one assumed that even though C was in principle variable, the variation was sufficiently slow that it can be moved out of the filtering operation ${\widehat {C(.)}}=C{\widehat {(.)}}$ .
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] Second, since C was a scalar, the Germano identity was contracted with a second rank tensor (the rate of strain tensor was chosen) to convert it to a scalar equation from which C could be determined.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] Lilly found a less arbitrary and therefore more satisfactory approach for obtaining C from the tensor identity.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] He noted that the Germano identity required the satisfaction of nine equations at each point in space (of which only five are independent) for a single quantity C .
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] The problem of obtaining C was therefore over-determined.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] He proposed therefore that C be determined using a least square fit by minimizing the residuals.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] First, the computed coefficient was not at all "slowly varying" as assumed and varied as much as any other turbulent field.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] Secondly, the computed C could be positive as well as negative.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] A slight preponderance of positive values as opposed to strict positivity of the eddy-viscosity results in the observed net dissipation.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] This so-called "backscatter" of energy from small to large scales indeed corresponds to negative C values in the Smagorinsky model.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] Nevertheless, the Germano-Lilly formulation was found not to result in stable calculations.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] When the averaging involved a large enough statistical sample that the computed C was positive (or at least only rarely negative) stable calculations were possible.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] Simply setting the negative values to zero (a procedure called "clipping") with or without the averaging also resulted in stable calculations.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] Meneveau proposed an averaging over Lagrangian fluid trajectories with an exponentially decaying "memory".
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] This can be applied to problems lacking homogeneous directions and can be stable if the effective time over which the averaging is done is long enough and yet not so long as to smooth out spatial inhomogenieties of interest.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] Lilly's modification of the Germano method followed by a statistical averaging or synthetic removal of negative viscosity regions seems ad hoc, even if it could be made to "work".
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] An alternate formulation of the least square minimization procedure known as the "Dynamic Localization Model" (DLM) was suggested by Ghosal et al.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] with the tensors $\tau _{ij}$ and $T_{ij}$ replaced by the appropriate SGS model.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] This tensor then represents the amount by which the subgrid model fails to respect the Germano identity at each spatial location.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] making $E_{ij}$ an algebraic function of C which is then determined by requiring that $E_{ij}E_{ij}$ considered as a function of C have the least possible value.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] However, since the C thus obtained turns out to be just as variable as any other fluctuating quantity in turbulence, the original assumption of the constancy of C cannot be justified a posteriori.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] In the DLM approach one avoids this inconsistency by not invoking the step of removing C from the test filtering operation.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] where the integral ranges over the whole fluid volume.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] This global error $E[C(x,y,z,t)]$ is then a functional of the spatially varying function $C(x,y,z,t)$ (here the time instant, t , is fixed and therefore appears just as a parameter) which is determined so as to minimize this functional.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] where the functions $K({\boldsymbol {x}},{\boldsymbol {y}})$ and $f({\boldsymbol {x}})$ are defined in terms of the resolved fields $L_{ij},\alpha _{ij},\beta _{ij}$ and are therefore known at each time step and the integral ranges over the whole fluid domain.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] The integral equation is solved numerically by an iteration procedure and convergence was found to be generally rapid if used with a pre-conditioning scheme.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] Even though this variational approach removes an inherent inconsistency in Lilly's approach, the $C(x,y,z,t)$ obtained from the integral equation still displayed the instability associated with negative viscosities.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] This can be resolved by insisting that $E[C]$ be minimized subject to the constraint $C(x,y,z,t)\geq 0$ .
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] Here the suffix + indicates the "positive part of" that is, $x_{+}=(x+|x|)/2$ .
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] Even though this superficially looks like "clipping" it is not an ad hoc scheme but a bonafide solution of the constrained variational problem.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] This DLM(+) model was found to be stable and yielded excellent results for forced and decaying isotropic turbulence, channel flows and a variety of other more complex geometries.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] If a flow happens to have homogeneous directions (let us say the directions x and z) then one can introduce the ansatz $C=C(y,t)$ .
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] The variational approach then immediately yields Lilly's result with averaging over homogeneous directions without any need for ad hoc modifications of a prior result.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] One shortcoming of the DLM(+) model was that it did not describe backscatter which is known to be a real "thing" from analyzing DNS data.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] Two approaches were developed to address this.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] In one approach due to Carati et al. a fluctuating force with amplitude determined by the fluctuation-dissipation theorem is added in analogy to Landau's theory of fluctuating hydrodynamics.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] In the second approach, one notes that any "backscattered" energy appears in the resolved scales only at the expense of energy in the subgrid scales.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] The DLM can be modified in a simple way to take into account this physical fact so as to allow for backscatter while being inherently stable.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] This k-equation version of the DLM, DLM(k) replaces $\Delta |{\bar {S}}|$ in the Smagorinsky eddy viscosity model by ${\sqrt {k}}$ as an appropriate velocity scale.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] where $\nu$ is the kinematic viscosity and $C_{*},D$ are positive coefficients representing kinetic energy dissipation and diffusion respectively.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] These can be determined following the dynamic procedure with constrained minimization as in DLM(+).
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] This approach, though more expensive to implement than the DLM(+) was found to be stable and resulted in good agreement with experimental data for a variety of flows tested.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] Furthermore, it is mathematically impossible for the DLM(k) to result in an unstable computation as the sum of the large scale and SGS energies is non-increasing by construction.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] Both of these approaches incorporating backscatter works well.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] They yield models that are slightly less dissipative with somewhat improved performance over the DLM(+).
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] The DLM(k) model additionally yields the subgrid kinetic energy, which may be a physical quantity of interest.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] These improvements are achieved at a somewhat increased cost in model implementation.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] The Dynamic Model originated at the 1990 Summer Program of the Center for Turbulence Research (CTR) at Stanford University.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/large-eddy-simulation] A series of "CTR-Tea" seminars celebrated the 30th Anniversary Archived 2022-10-30 at the Wayback Machine of this important milestone in turbulence modeling.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] The transition from laminar (left) to turbulent (right) flow of water from a tap occurs as the Reynolds number increases.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] In fluid dynamics, the **Reynolds number** (**Re**) is a dimensionless quantity that helps predict fluid flow patterns in different situations by measuring the ratio between inertial and viscous forces.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] At low Reynolds numbers, flows tend to be dominated by laminar (sheet-like) flow, while at high Reynolds numbers, flows tend to be turbulent.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] The turbulence results from differences in the fluid's speed and direction, which may sometimes intersect or even move counter to the overall direction of the flow (eddy currents).
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] These eddy currents begin to churn the flow, using up energy in the process, which for liquids increases the chances of cavitation.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] The Reynolds number has wide applications, ranging from liquid flow in a pipe to the passage of air over an aircraft wing.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] It is used to predict the transition from laminar to turbulent flow and is used in the scaling of similar but different-sized flow situations, such as between an aircraft model in a wind tunnel and the full-size version.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] The predictions of the onset of turbulence and the ability to calculate scaling effects can be used to help predict fluid behavior on a larger scale, such as in local or global air or water movement, and thereby the associated meteorological and climatological effects.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] The concept was introduced by George Stokes in 1851, but the Reynolds number was named by Arnold Sommerfeld in 1908 after Osborne Reynolds who popularized its use in 1883 (an example of Stigler's law of eponymy).
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] The Reynolds number is the ratio of inertial forces to viscous forces within a fluid that is subjected to relative internal movement due to different fluid velocities.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] A region where these forces change behavior is known as a boundary layer, such as the bounding surface in the interior of a pipe.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] A similar effect is created by the introduction of a stream of high-velocity fluid into a low-velocity fluid, such as the hot gases emitted from a flame in air.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] This relative movement generates fluid friction, which is a factor in developing turbulent flow.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Counteracting this effect is the viscosity of the fluid, which tends to inhibit turbulence.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] The Reynolds number quantifies the relative importance of these two types of forces for given flow conditions and is a guide to when turbulent flow will occur in a particular situation.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Such scaling is not linear and the application of Reynolds numbers to both situations allows scaling factors to be developed.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] These are generally not independent numbers: liquids generally get less viscous as they become hotter, while gases generally become more viscous.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Both will generally become less dense as they become hotter, although the effect is substantially more pronounced in gases.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] For a (solid) object in a fluid, the characteristic length will vary with temperature - solids are typically even less temperature sensitive than liquids when it comes to density, but at sufficient flow speeds, the amount of frictional heat from traversing the fluid can be substantial.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] The Reynolds number can be defined for several different situations where a fluid is in relative motion to a surface.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] These definitions generally include the fluid properties of density and viscosity, plus a velocity and a characteristic length or characteristic dimension (L in the above equation).
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] This dimension is a matter of convention—for example radius and diameter are equally valid to describe spheres or circles, but one is chosen by convention.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] For aircraft or ships, the length or width can be used.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] For flow in a pipe, or for a sphere moving in a fluid, the internal diameter is generally used today.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Other shapes such as rectangular pipes or non-spherical objects have an *equivalent diameter* defined.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] For fluids of variable density such as compressible gases or fluids of variable viscosity such as non-Newtonian fluids, special rules apply.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] The velocity may also be a matter of convention in some circumstances, notably stirred vessels.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] In practice, matching the Reynolds number is not on its own sufficient to guarantee similitude.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Fluid flow is generally chaotic, and very small changes to shape and surface roughness of bounding surfaces can result in very different flows.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Nevertheless, Reynolds numbers are a very important guide and are widely used.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] If we know that the relevant physical quantities in a physical system are only $\rho ,u,L,\mu$ , then the Reynolds number is essentially fixed by the Buckingham π theorem.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Setting the three dimensions of $\rho ^{x_{1}}u^{x_{2}}L^{x_{3}}\mu ^{x_{4}}$ to zero, we obtain 3 independent linear constraints, so the solution space has 1 dimension, and it is spanned by the vector $(1,1,1,-1)$ .
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Thus, any dimensionless quantity constructed out of $\rho ,u,L,\mu$ is a function of $\rho uL\mu ^{-1}$ , the Reynolds number.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] This argument is written out in detail on the Scallop theorem page.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Each term in the above equation has the units of a "body force" (force per unit volume) with the same dimensions of a density multiplied by an acceleration.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Each term is thus dependent on the exact measurements of a flow.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] When we render the equation nondimensional, that is when we multiply it by a factor with inverse units of the base equation, we obtain a form that does not depend directly on the physical sizes.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] This is why mathematically all Newtonian, incompressible flows with the same Reynolds number are comparable.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Notice also that in the above equation, the viscous terms vanish for Re → ∞.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Thus flows with high Reynolds numbers are approximately inviscid in the free stream.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Osborne Reynolds famously studied the conditions in which the flow of fluid in pipes transitioned from laminar flow to turbulent flow.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] In his 1883 paper, Reynolds described the transition from laminar to turbulent flow in a classic experiment in which he examined the behaviour of water flow under different flow velocities using a small stream of dyed water introduced into the centre of clear water flow in a larger pipe.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] The larger pipe was made of glass so the behaviour of the layer of the dyed stream could be observed.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] At the end of this pipe, there was a flow control valve used to vary the water velocity inside the tube.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] When the velocity was low, the dyed layer remained distinct throughout the entire length of the large tube.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] When the velocity was increased, the layer broke up at a given point and diffused throughout the fluid's cross-section.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] The point at which this happened was the transition point from laminar to turbulent flow.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] From these experiments came the dimensionless Reynolds number for dynamic similarity –the ratio of inertial forces to viscous forces.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Reynolds also proposed what is now known as the Reynolds averaging of turbulent flows, where quantities such as velocity are expressed as the sum of mean and fluctuating components.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Such averaging allows for 'bulk' description of turbulent flow, for example using the Reynolds-averaged Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] where *A* is the cross-sectional area, and *P* is the wetted perimeter.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] The wetted perimeter for a channel is the total perimeter of all channel walls that are in contact with the flow.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] This means that the length of the channel exposed to air is *not* included in the wetted perimeter.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] For calculation involving flow in non-circular ducts, the hydraulic diameter can be substituted for the diameter of a circular duct, with reasonable accuracy, if the aspect ratio AR of the duct cross-section remains in the range ⁠1/4⁠ < AR < 4.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] In boundary layer flow over a flat plate, experiments confirm that, after a certain length of flow, a laminar boundary layer will become unstable and turbulent.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] This instability occurs across different scales and with different fluids, usually when Re*x* ≈ 5×105, where *x* is the distance from the leading edge of the flat plate, and the flow velocity is the freestream velocity of the fluid outside the boundary layer.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] For flow in a pipe of diameter *D*, experimental observations show that for "fully developed" flow, laminar flow occurs when Re*D* < 2300 and turbulent flow occurs when Re*D* > 2900.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] At the lower end of this range, a continuous turbulent-flow will form, but only at a very long distance from the inlet of the pipe.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] The flow in between will begin to transition from laminar to turbulent and then back to laminar at irregular intervals, called intermittent flow.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] This is due to the different speeds and conditions of the fluid in different areas of the pipe's cross-section, depending on other factors such as pipe roughness and flow uniformity.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Laminar flow tends to dominate in the fast-moving center of the pipe while slower-moving turbulent flow dominates near the wall.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] As the Reynolds number increases, the continuous turbulent-flow moves closer to the inlet and the intermittency in between increases, until the flow becomes fully turbulent at Re*D* > 2900.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] This result is generalized to non-circular channels using the hydraulic diameter, allowing a transition Reynolds number to be calculated for other shapes of channel.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] These transition Reynolds numbers are also called *critical Reynolds numbers*, and were studied by Osborne Reynolds around 1895.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] The critical Reynolds number is different for every geometry.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] For a fluid moving between two plane parallel surfaces—where the width is much greater than the space between the plates—then the characteristic dimension is equal to the distance between the plates.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] This is consistent with the annular duct and rectangular duct cases above, taken to a limiting aspect ratio.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] For calculating the flow of liquid with a free surface, the hydraulic radius must be determined.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] This is the cross-sectional area of the channel divided by the wetted perimeter.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] For a semi-circular channel, it is a quarter of the diameter (in case of full pipe flow).
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] For a rectangular channel, the hydraulic radius is the cross-sectional area divided by the wetted perimeter.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Reynolds numbers are used in airfoil design to (among other things) manage "scale effect" when computing/comparing characteristics (a tiny wing, scaled to be huge, will perform differently).
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Fluid dynamicists define the *chord Reynolds number* *R* = *Vc*/*ν*, where *V* is the flight speed, *c* is the chord length, and *ν* is the kinematic viscosity of the fluid in which the airfoil operates, which is 1.460×10−5 m2/s for the atmosphere at sea level.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] In some special studies a characteristic length other than chord may be used; rare is the "span Reynolds number", which is not to be confused with span-wise stations on a wing, where chord is still used.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] The Reynolds number for an object moving in a fluid, called the particle Reynolds number and often denoted Rep, characterizes the nature of the surrounding flow and its fall velocity.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Where the viscosity is naturally high, such as polymer solutions and polymer melts, flow is normally laminar.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] The Reynolds number is very small and Stokes' law can be used to measure the viscosity of the fluid.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Spheres are allowed to fall through the fluid and they reach the terminal velocity quickly, from which the viscosity can be determined.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] The laminar flow of polymer solutions is exploited by animals such as fish and dolphins, who exude viscous solutions from their skin to aid flow over their bodies while swimming.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] It has been used in yacht racing by owners who want to gain a speed advantage by pumping a polymer solution such as low molecular weight polyoxyethylene in water, over the wetted surface of the hull.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] It is, however, a problem for mixing polymers, because turbulence is needed to distribute fine filler (for example) through the material.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Inventions such as the "cavity transfer mixer" have been developed to produce multiple folds into a moving melt so as to improve mixing efficiency.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] The device can be fitted onto extruders to aid mixing.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] For a sphere in a fluid, the characteristic length-scale is the diameter of the sphere and the characteristic velocity is that of the sphere relative to the fluid some distance away from the sphere, such that the motion of the sphere does not disturb that reference parcel of fluid.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] The density and viscosity are those belonging to the fluid.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Note that purely laminar flow only exists up to Re = 10 under this definition.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Under the condition of low Re, the relationship between force and speed of motion is given by Stokes' law.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] At higher Reynolds numbers the drag on a sphere depends on surface roughness.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Thus, for example, adding dimples on the surface of a golf ball causes the boundary layer on the upstream side of the ball to transition from laminar to turbulent.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] The turbulent boundary layer is able to remain attached to the surface of the ball much longer than a laminar boundary and so creates a narrower low-pressure wake and hence less pressure drag.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] The reduction in pressure drag causes the ball to travel farther.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] The equation for a rectangular object is identical to that of a sphere, with the object being approximated as an ellipsoid and the axis of length being chosen as the characteristic length scale.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Such considerations are important in natural streams, for example, where there are few perfectly spherical grains.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] For grains in which measurement of each axis is impractical, sieve diameters are used instead as the characteristic particle length-scale.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Both approximations alter the values of the critical Reynolds number.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] The particle Reynolds number is important in determining the terminal velocity of a particle.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] When the particle Reynolds number indicates laminar flow, Stokes' law can be used to calculate its fall velocity or settling velocity.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] When the particle Reynolds number indicates turbulent flow, a turbulent drag law must be constructed to model the appropriate settling velocity.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Laminar conditions apply up to Re = 10, fully turbulent from Re = 2000.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] In a cylindrical vessel stirred by a central rotating paddle, turbine or propeller, the characteristic dimension is the diameter of the agitator *D*.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] The velocity *V* is *ND* where *N* is the rotational speed in rad per second.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] The system is fully turbulent for values of Re above 10000.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Pressure drops seen for fully developed flow of fluids through pipes can be predicted using the Moody diagram which plots the Darcy–Weisbach friction factor *f* against Reynolds number Re and relative roughness ⁠*ε*/*D*⁠.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] The diagram clearly shows the laminar, transition, and turbulent flow regimes as Reynolds number increases.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] The nature of pipe flow is strongly dependent on whether the flow is laminar or turbulent.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] In order for two flows to be similar, they must have the same geometry and equal Reynolds and Euler numbers.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] where $\mathrm {Re} _{\text{m}}$ is the Reynolds number for the model, and $\mathrm {Re}$ is full-scale Reynolds number, and similarly for the Euler numbers.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] This allows engineers to perform experiments with reduced scale models in water channels or wind tunnels and correlate the data to the actual flows, saving on costs during experimentation and on lab time.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Note that true dynamic similitude may require matching other dimensionless numbers as well, such as the Mach number used in compressible flows, or the Froude number that governs open-channel flows.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Some flows involve more dimensionless parameters than can be practically satisfied with the available apparatus and fluids, so one is forced to decide which parameters are most important.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] For experimental flow modeling to be useful, it requires a fair amount of experience and judgment of the engineer.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] An example where the mere Reynolds number is not sufficient for the similarity of flows (or even the flow regime – laminar or turbulent) are bounded flows, i.e. flows that are restricted by walls or other boundaries.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] A classical example of this is the Taylor–Couette flow, where the dimensionless ratio of radii of bounding cylinders is also important, and many technical applications where these distinctions play an important role.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Principles of these restrictions were developed by Maurice Marie Alfred Couette and Geoffrey Ingram Taylor and developed further by Floris Takens and David Ruelle.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] In a turbulent flow, there is a range of scales of the time-varying fluid motion.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] The size of the largest scales of fluid motion (sometimes called eddies) are set by the overall geometry of the flow.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] For instance, in an industrial smoke stack, the largest scales of fluid motion are as big as the diameter of the stack itself.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] The size of the smallest scales is set by the Reynolds number.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] As the Reynolds number increases, smaller and smaller scales of the flow are visible.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] In a smokestack, the smoke may appear to have many very small velocity perturbations or eddies, in addition to large bulky eddies.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] In this sense, the Reynolds number is an indicator of the range of scales in the flow.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] The higher the Reynolds number, the greater the range of scales.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] The largest eddies will always be the same size; the smallest eddies are determined by the Reynolds number.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] What is the explanation for this phenomenon?
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] A large Reynolds number indicates that viscous forces are not important at large scales of the flow.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] With a strong predominance of inertial forces over viscous forces, the largest scales of fluid motion are undamped—there is not enough viscosity to dissipate their motions.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] The kinetic energy must "cascade" from these large scales to progressively smaller scales until a level is reached for which the scale is small enough for viscosity to become important (that is, viscous forces become of the order of inertial ones).
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] It is at these small scales where the dissipation of energy by viscous action finally takes place.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] The Reynolds number indicates at what scale this viscous dissipation occurs.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Poiseuille's law on blood circulation in the body is dependent on laminar flow.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] In turbulent flow the flow rate is proportional to the square root of the pressure gradient, as opposed to its direct proportionality to pressure gradient in laminar flow.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Using the definition of the Reynolds number we can see that a large diameter with rapid flow, where the density of the blood is high, tends towards turbulence.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Rapid changes in vessel diameter may lead to turbulent flow, for instance when a narrower vessel widens to a larger one.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Furthermore, a bulge of atheroma may be the cause of turbulent flow, where audible turbulence may be detected with a stethoscope.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Reynolds number interpretation has been extended into the area of arbitrary complex systems.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Such as financial flows, nonlinear networks, etc.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] In the latter case, an artificial viscosity is reduced to a nonlinear mechanism of energy distribution in complex network media.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Reynolds number then represents a basic control parameter that expresses a balance between injected and dissipated energy flows for an open boundary system.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] It has been shown that Reynolds critical regime separates two types of phase space motion: accelerator (attractor) and decelerator.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] High Reynolds number leads to a chaotic regime transition only in frame of strange attractor model.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] There are many dimensionless numbers in fluid mechanics.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] The Reynolds number measures the ratio of advection and diffusion effects on structures in the velocity field, and is therefore closely related to Péclet numbers, which measure the ratio of these effects on other fields carried by the flow, for example, temperature and magnetic fields.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] Replacement of the kinematic viscosity *ν* = ⁠*μ*/*ρ*⁠ in Re by the thermal or magnetic diffusivity results in respectively the thermal Péclet number and the magnetic Reynolds number.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/reynolds-number] These are therefore related to Re by-products with ratios of diffusivities, namely the Prandtl number and magnetic Prandtl number.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/turbulence-modeling] In fluid dynamics, **turbulence modeling** is the construction and use of a mathematical model to predict the effects of turbulence.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/turbulence-modeling] Turbulent flows are commonplace in most real-life scenarios.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/turbulence-modeling] In spite of decades of research, there is no analytical theory to predict the evolution of these turbulent flows.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/turbulence-modeling] The equations governing turbulent flows can only be solved directly for simple cases of flow.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/turbulence-modeling] For most real-life turbulent flows, CFD simulations use turbulent models to predict the evolution of turbulence.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/turbulence-modeling] These turbulence models are simplified constitutive equations that predict the statistical evolution of turbulent flows.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/turbulence-modeling] The Navier–Stokes equations govern the velocity and pressure of a fluid flow.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/turbulence-modeling] In a turbulent flow, each of these quantities may be decomposed into a mean part and a fluctuating part.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/turbulence-modeling] Averaging the equations gives the Reynolds-averaged Navier–Stokes (RANS) equations, which govern the mean flow.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/turbulence-modeling] However, the nonlinearity of the Navier–Stokes equations means that the velocity fluctuations still appear in the RANS equations, in the nonlinear term $-\rho {\overline {v_{i}^{\prime }v_{j}^{\prime }}}$ from the convective acceleration.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/turbulence-modeling] This term is known as the Reynolds stress, $R_{ij}$ .
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/turbulence-modeling] Its effect on the mean flow is like that of a stress term, such as from pressure or viscosity.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/turbulence-modeling] To obtain equations containing only the mean velocity and pressure, we need to close the RANS equations by modelling the Reynolds stress term $R_{ij}$ as a function of the mean flow, removing any reference to the fluctuating part of the velocity.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/turbulence-modeling] Joseph Valentin Boussinesq was the first to attack the closure problem, by introducing the concept of eddy viscosity.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/turbulence-modeling] In 1877 Boussinesq proposed relating the turbulence stresses to the mean flow to close the system of equations.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/turbulence-modeling] Here the Boussinesq hypothesis is applied to model the Reynolds stress term.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/turbulence-modeling] Note that a new proportionality constant $\nu _{t}>0$ , the *(kinematic) turbulence eddy viscosity*, has been introduced.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/turbulence-modeling] Models of this type are known as eddy viscosity models (EVMs).
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/turbulence-modeling] In this model, the additional turbulence stresses are given by augmenting the molecular viscosity with an eddy viscosity.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/turbulence-modeling] This can be a simple constant eddy viscosity (which works well for some free shear flows such as axisymmetric jets, 2-D jets, and mixing layers).
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/turbulence-modeling] It has since been found to be significantly less accurate than most practitioners would assume.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/turbulence-modeling] Still, turbulence models which employ the Boussinesq hypothesis have demonstrated significant practical value.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/turbulence-modeling] In cases with well-defined shear layers, this is likely due the dominance of streamwise shear components, so that considerable *relative* errors in flow-normal components are still negligible in *absolute* terms.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/turbulence-modeling] Beyond this, most eddy viscosity turbulence models contain coefficients which are calibrated against measurements, and thus produce reasonably accurate overall outcomes for flow fields of similar type as used for calibration.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/turbulence-modeling] Later, Ludwig Prandtl introduced the additional concept of the mixing length, along with the idea of a boundary layer.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/turbulence-modeling] For wall-bounded turbulent flows, the eddy viscosity must vary with distance from the wall, hence the addition of the concept of a 'mixing length'.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/turbulence-modeling] This simple model is the basis for the "law of the wall", which is a surprisingly accurate model for wall-bounded, attached (not separated) flow fields with small pressure gradients.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/turbulence-modeling] More general turbulence models have evolved over time, with most modern turbulence models given by field equations similar to the Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/turbulence-modeling] In the context of Large Eddy Simulation, turbulence modeling refers to the need to parameterize the subgrid scale stress in terms of features of the filtered velocity field.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/turbulence-modeling] This field is called subgrid-scale modeling.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/turbulence-modeling] The Boussinesq hypothesis is employed in the Spalart–Allmaras (S–A), *k*–ε (*k*–epsilon), and *k*–ω (*k*–omega) models and offers a relatively low cost computation for the turbulence viscosity $\nu _{t}$ .
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/turbulence-modeling] The S–A model uses only one additional equation to model turbulence viscosity transport, while the *k*–ε and *k*–ω models use two.
[src:computational-fluid-dynamics/turbulence-modeling] The following is a brief overview of commonly employed models in modern engineering applications.
